metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: MEGDAZ II #110
metadata.description:
Welcome to Megdaz II - one the most beautiful of all Central High Atlas area of Morocco.

I wanted to create an animated version of Megdaz - subtile movements but still interesting enough to observe the whole scene.

This artwork shows Megdaz as abstract town at different times and places:
- cafe terrace at night
- at the pool
- at the river
- before a mirror
- at the central park
- end of summer
- supper at Emmaus
- at the melting pot
- at the game

The canvas resolution is 4096x4096

--

Generative Art created by Michael Vogt (@neophob).

metadata.name: Miniscapes #296
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #115
metadata.description:
‚ÄúShapes on a Plane‚Äù explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It‚Äôs intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I‚Äôd spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i‚Äôd take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I‚Äôd have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #5
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Girandola #36
metadata.description:
Girandola is a project that strives to show the strength of programming to create very full and complex art using simple shapes, colors and iteration.

The concept of drawing shapes around an expanding radius, en masse, with different colors, rotations, outlines and opacities is all we have here. Highly variable, with outputs ranging from thousands to close to 1 million shapes can produce a vast array of imagery that would be impossible without the power of iteration that only digital art can provide.

Controls
--------
[mouse click] - start/stop the sketch
[r] - redraw the sketch
[s] - save a .png

URL Params
----------
?size=xxxx where xxxx is a size in pixels you'd like to render

metadata.name: Rambling #22
metadata.description:
Step into the enchanting realm of "Rambling", where vibrant lines dance and collide in an ever-changing composition. This generative canvas invites you to immerse yourself in the vibrant chaos as it weaves a symphony of color that resonates with the soul.

The collection was created in honor of my "Schiftcopy" birthday today, August 18, for all collectors who have supported my efforts for 11 months.

Made with p5js by Schiftcopy 2023

50% Royalties split for minters

metadata.name: Perpendicular Inhabitation #69
metadata.description:
'Perpendicular Inhabitation' is a generative collection exploring the relationship between the urban landscape and the human experience, particularly feelings of nostalgia and more specifically 'anemoia' : the feeling of nostalgia for a time or place that we may not have actually experienced first hand. 

Despite depicting a stylised modern architectural language, at its core the collection serves as a homage to 1980s Japan, an era of unprecedented prosperity that left a lasting impression on the music and artwork of the time. Through the use of carefully created palettes and composition, the outputs intend to evoke feelings of optimism, while guiding viewers to consider why the essence of this era is so alluring in the present day as it continues to influence and inspire contemporary art.

The use of exaggerated perpendicular verticals, as well as the heavily foreshortened mountain ranges present in some outputs, convey a sense of hope and possibility for the future. What does it feel like to hope and dream in the city? To look up and be filled with a sense of wonder from the built environment around you?

This project has been created with print in mind at a ratio of 3:4

It is recommended to examine your outputs at full size in order to enjoy them to the fullest.

You are encouraged to return often to notice things you may not have seen previously.

Generated with code using p5.js

Images are generated at 2400 x 3200 px. 

To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

Depending on the complexity of each output, please wait up to 10 seconds for the image generation to complete.

metadata.name: Polygons in Harmony #58
metadata.description:
This piece is crafted with p5js. It is a collection of polygons randomly arranged in a regular grid. Each of them has the possibility to be drawn with a specific pattern inside, adding more variety to the generated image. It features different colors for the canvas, as well as themes for the distribution of the polygons.

To download the image, press [s]

metadata.name: Slumbers #219
metadata.description:
Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Options:

- press 'f' to turn off paper-like texture (recommended for print on hi-quality paper)
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Colors and textures might differ slightly on some devices due to the heavy use of low alpha blending. Calibrated and tested on Firefox 107.0 & Chrome 107.0.5304.107 on Win10 x64 Intel machine.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.
tags: slumbers volatile moods abstract generative painting colors brushwork

metadata.name: Rural Places #41
metadata.description:
Continuing my exploration of abstract minimalism, this artwork is fully developed using p5js (100% code). Rural Places is a meditation in the form of abstract minimalism. There are 6 types of buildings and structures such as windmills and water towers and multiple houses with different structures and styles in this artwork. There are various arrangements and color palettes based on different times of the day.

To see the artwork in full size, It's highly recommended to open it in live mode.

You can save the artwork by pressing 's' in live view after render was completed.

metadata.name: Manifold #9
metadata.description:
Manifold
Each piece is created using particles in a custom flow field. The particles form intricate patterns resembling light caustics. 
As a minter, you can decide the color of your piece, which significantly impacts the feel of the piece!
Created by Mathbird in P5.js!
I hope you enjoy your piece!
